Machine Learning¶

  • Machine Learning is the area of Computer Science that seeks to find ways so that computer can learn by themselves, without us having to program them.

  • There are three main areas:

    • Supervised learning
    • Unsupervised learning
    • Reinforcement learning

Supervised Learning¶

  • In supervised learning, we give the computer a set of example problems along with their solutions.

  • The computer must then find the way so that given new problems, that it has not seen before, it can find their solutions.

  • We therefore start with a training phase. After that we go to a testing phase, where we use the trained computer against some holdout data, to check its perfomance. Then we can go to production.

  • Examples of supervised learning:

    • Classification
    • Decision trees
    • Bayesian networks
    • Artificial neural networks
    • ...

Support Vector Machines¶

  • Support Vector Machines (SVM) is an approach to classification developed in the 1990s.

  • It is very popular, so it is a good vehicle to start exploring Machine Learning.

  • To see what they are, we must talk about Maximal Margin Classifiers and Support Vector Classifiers.

Maximal Margin Classifiers¶

  • We want to separate our observations into two classes.

  • If our observations have $p$ features, or dimensions, they can be separated by a $p-1$ dimensional hyperplane.

  • We try to find the best hyperplane.

  • We compute the perpendicular distance from each observation to the candidate hyperplane. The smallest of these distances is called the margin.

  • We select the hyperplane with the maximal margin.

  • The mathematical formulation is: $$\text{maximimize } M(\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_p)$$ subject to: $$\sum_{j=1}^{p}{\beta_j^2 = 1}$$ $$y_i(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \ldots + \beta_p x_{ip}) \ge M$$ for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$ and $y \in \{-1 , +1\}$.

  • In the following slide you can see three different hyperplanes and two different classes.

  • $\textrm{H}_1$ does not separate the black class.

  • $\textrm{H}_2$ and $\textrm{H}_3$ both separate the two classes.

  • $\textrm{H}_3$ does a better job, because it separates the classes with a wider margin.

Support Vector Classifiers¶

  • Support Vector Classifiers are a generalisation of Maximal Margin Classifiers.

  • Instead of trying to find the biggest margin, it allows some observations to lie on the wrong side of the margin, even on the wrong side of the hyperplane.

  • In this we achieve greater robustness to invividual observations and better classification of most of the observations.

  • The mathematical formulation is: $$\text{maximimize } M(\beta_0, \beta_1, \beta_p)$$ subject to: $$\sum_{j=1}^{p}{\beta_j^2 = 1}$$ $$y_i(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \ldots + \beta_p x_{ip}) \ge (M - \epsilon_i)$$ $$ \epsilon_i \ge 0$$ $$ \sum_{i=1}^{n}\epsilon_i \le C$$ for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$ and $y \in \{-1 , +1\}$.

  • Note that if $\epsilon_i = 0$, then the $i$th observation lies on the correct side of the hyperplane.

  • If $C = 0$, there can be no violations.

  • If $C > 0$, then no more than $C$ observations can be on the wrong side of the hyperplane (if an observation is on the wrong side, then $\epsilon_i > 1$).

  • The observations that lie on the margin, or on the wrong side of the margin are called support vectors, because they affect the classifier (the rest do not).

Support Vector Machines¶

  • Support Vector Machines are a generalisation of Support Vector Classifiers.

  • Instead of trying to find the biggest margin, it allows some observations to lie on the wrong side of the margin, even on the wrong side of the hyperplane.

  • In this we achieve greater robustness to invividual observations and better classification of most of the observations.

  • It can be shown that the Support Vector Classifier can be represented as: $$ f(x) = \beta_0 + \sum_{i = 1}^{n}\alpha_i\langle x, x_i \rangle$$ for $n$ parameters $a\_i$, one per training observation.

  • To estimate the parameters we work with the inner products $\langle x_i, x_i'\rangle$ between any pair $x_i, x_i'$ of training observations.

  • Now we generalize, and we allow ourselves to use other functions, and not just inner products.

  • So we have: $$ f(x) = \beta_0 + \sum_{i = 1}^{n}\alpha_i K(x, x_i) $$

  • $K(\cdot, \cdot)$ is called a kernel.

  • If $K(x_i, x_j) = \sum_{i = 1}^n x_{ij}x_{i'j}$, then we have an inner product, which is a linear kernel, and so we get a Support Vector Classifier.

  • But if $K(\cdot, \cdot)$ is not linear in the features, we get a Support Vector Machine.

  • Support Vector Machines can classify observations that are not linear separable.

  • Common kernels are:
    • linear: $\langle x, x'\rangle$.
    • polynomial: $(\gamma \langle x, x'\rangle + r)^d$
    • radial: $\exp(-\gamma |x-x'|^2)$.
    • sigmoid: $\tanh(\gamma \langle x,x'\rangle + r)$

SVMs with Many Classes¶

  • If we have more than two classes, we can work with the following strategies:
    • One-versus-One Classification
    • One-versus-All Classification

One-versus-One Classification¶

  • In One-versus-One (OvO) classification for $K$ classes, we create $\binom{K}{2} = \frac{K(K-1)}{2}$ SVMs.

  • Each one of them classifies observation for a distinct pair of classes.

  • We tally the classes assigned for each observation.

  • In the end, we assign to each observation the class with the maximum tally.

One-versus-All Classification¶

  • In One-versus-All (OvA) a.k.a. One-versus-Rest (OvR) classification for $K$ classes, we create $K$ SVMs.

  • In each one of them, we classify observations in one class versus all the other $K - 1$ classes lumped together.

  • In the end, we assign to each observation the class with the maximum distance from the hyperplane.

Scikit-learn¶

  • scikit-learn is a Machine Learning toolkit in Python.

  • In their own words:

    • It started in 2007 as a Google Summer of Code project by David Cournapeau. Later that year, Matthieu Brucher started work on this project as part of his thesis.

    • In 2010 Fabian Pedregosa, Gael Varoquaux, Alexandre Gramfort and Vincent Michel of INRIA took leadership of the project and made the first public release, February the 1st 2010. Since then, several releases have appeared following a ~3 month cycle, and a thriving international community has been leading the development.

A Short Example¶

  • We'll build a classifier for handwritten digits.

  • We won't go into many details at this point; we just want to get an overview of scikit-learn.

  • scikit-learn comes with a number of datasets that we can use to get familiar with it.

  • A dataset is a dictionary-like object that holds all the data and some metadata about the data.

  • This data is stored in the data member, which is a n_samples, n_features array.

  • In the case of supervised problem, one or more response variables are stored in the target member.

  • In the case of the digits dataset, the task is to predict, given an image, which digit it represents.

  • We are given samples of each of the 10 possible classes (the digits zero through nine) on which we fit an estimator to be able to predict the classes to which unseen samples belong.

  • In scikit-learn, an estimator for classification is a Python object that implements the methods fit(X, y) and predict(T).

  • An example of an estimator is the class sklearn.svm.SVC that implements support vector classification. The constructor of an estimator takes as arguments the parameters of the model.

  • Note that SVC is hard to scale in samples larger that 10,000.

  • The sklearn.svm.SVC class uses as a default a radial basis function kernel.

  • The available choices are:

    • linear: $\langle x, x'\rangle$.
    • poly: $(\gamma \langle x, x'\rangle + r)^d$. $d$ is specified by the degree keyword, $r$ by the coef0 keyword.
    • rbf: $\exp(-\gamma |x-x'|^2)$. $\gamma$ is specified by the gamma keyword, must be greater than 0.
    • sigmoid: $\tanh(\gamma \langle x,x'\rangle + r)$, where $r$ is specified by the coef0 keyword.

  • Let us create a classification.

  • It will use the default, radial, kernel.

  • We'll set $\gamma = 0.001$ and the penalty term $C = 100$.

In [4]:
from sklearn import svm
clf = svm.SVC(gamma=0.001, C=100.)

  • We call our estimator instance clf, as it is a classifier.

  • It now must be fitted to the model, that is, it must learn from the model.

  • This is done by passing our training set to the fit method.

  • As a training set, let us use all the images of our dataset apart from the last one.

  • We select this training set with the [:-1] Python syntax, which produces a new array that contains all but the last entry of digits.data.

In [5]:
clf.fit(digits.data[:-1], digits.target[:-1])
Out[5]:
SVC(C=100.0, cache_size=200, class_weight=None, coef0=0.0,
  decision_function_shape=None, degree=3, gamma=0.001, kernel='rbf',
  max_iter=-1, probability=False, random_state=None, shrinking=True,
  tol=0.001, verbose=False)

  • cache_size: the cache used for the kernel function (in MB).

  • class_weight: use a weight of one for all classes, or adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies in the input data.

  • coef0: independent term in poly and sigmoid kernel functions.

  • decision_function_shape: ovo or ovr, default is None, which currently sets ovo (but will change to ovr in version 0.19).

  • degree: degree of the polynomial kernel.

  • gamma: kernel coefficient for rbf, poly and sigmoid.

  • kernel: kernel type; default is rbf.

  • max_iter: hard limits of itereations or -1 for no limit.

  • probability: whether to enable probability estimates.

  • random_state: seed.

  • shrinking: whether to use the shrinking heuristic; see Support Vector Machine Solvers.

  • Now we can predict new values.

  • In particular, we can ask to the classifier what is the digit of our last image in the digits dataset, which we have not used to train the classifier.

Linear Classification¶

  • We will try to predict the Iris ower species using only two attributes: sepal width and sepal length.

  • This is an instance of a classification problem, where we want to assign a label (a value taken from a discrete set) to an item according to its features.

  • To carry out the classification we will use the SGDClassifier.

  • SGD stands for Stochastic Gradient Descent. This is a numerical procedure to find the minimum of a function.

  • In our case it will find the minimum of the loss function, which measures how far every data instance is from the classification boundary.

  • The advantages of Stochastic Gradient Descent are:

    • Efficiency.
    • Ease of implementation (lots of opportunities for code tuning).

  • The disadvantages of Stochastic Gradient Descent include:

    • SGD requires a number of hyperparameters such as the regularization parameter and the number of iterations.
    • SGD is sensitive to feature scaling.

  • We'll use the famous Iris dataset.

  • The dataset is available inside the scikit-learn distribution.

In [15]:
iris = datasets.load_iris()
X_iris, y_iris = iris.data, iris.target
print(X_iris.shape, y_iris.shape)

(150, 4) (150,)

  • X_iris contains the sepal length, sepal width, petal length, and petal width and y_iris contains an array with values 0 to 2, corresponding to each instance of Iris species (0: setosa, 1: versicolor, and 2: virginica).

  • The meaning of the labels are in the target_names attribute.

  • The meaning of the features are in the feature_names attribute.

  • The full dataset description is the the DESCR attribute.

The famous Iris database, first used by Sir R.A Fisher

This is perhaps the best known database to be found in the
pattern recognition literature.  Fisher's paper is a classic in the field and
is referenced frequently to this day.  (See Duda & Hart, for example.)  The
data set contains 3 classes of 50 instances each, where each class refers to a
type of iris plant.  One class is linearly separable from the other 2; the
latter are NOT linearly separable from each other.

  • First we'll need to shuffle the data, because samples with the same labels are continuous.
In [18]:
idx = np.arange(X_iris.shape[0])
np.random.seed(13)
np.random.shuffle(idx)
X = X_iris[:, :2] # take only sepal length and width
X = X[idx]
y = y_iris[idx]

  • Stochastic Gradient Descent is sensitive to feature scaling, so it is highly recommended to scale our data.

  • In particular we should scale each attribute on the input vector X to [0,1] or [-1,+1], or standardise it to have mean 0 and variance 1; various Machine Learning methods assume that data have that mean and variance.

  • This can be easily done using StandardScaler.

  • StandarScaler scales the data so that they have mean 0 and variance equal to 1.

In [19]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X)
X = scaler.transform(X)
  • Now we can build our classifier.
In [20]:
from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier

clf = SGDClassifier(alpha=0.001, n_iter=100).fit(X, y)

  • The resulf of the classification is in the clf object.

  • Since we are trying to classify three classes, the clf object contains the information for the three lines that divide our data instances.

$$ -2.68706676 - 4.15181168 x_1 + 2.07696312 x_2 = 0 $$$$ -0.72485109 + 0.08196641 x_1 - 1.19171515 x_2 = 0 $$$$ -0.87117313 + 1.69361769 x_1 - 0.0445216 x_2 = 0 $$

  • To see the classification, we'll plot a mesh grid.

  • The mesh grid will show the surfaces that correspond to the classification labels.

In [23]:
h = .02  # step size in the mesh

sepal_length_min, sepal_length_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
sepal_width_min, sepal_width_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(sepal_length_min, sepal_length_max, h),
                     np.arange(sepal_width_min, sepal_width_max, h))

  • We'll then predict the classification labels for all the values in the mesh.

  • To do that we need to flatten xx and yy and then zip them, so that we feed to predict an array containing pairs of sepal length and sepal width values.

  • The decision is based on the distance between the classifier line and the instance.

  • The predict method calculates the distance, between each observation and the line, and selects the class of the line with the largest distance.

In [24]:
xx_yy = np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()] # zip the xx and yy values
Z = clf.predict(xx_yy)

  • Having done that we can now make a contour plot with the predicted classifications.

    ymin = (-(xmin * coef[i, 0]) - intercept[i]) / coef[i, 1]
    ymax = (-(xmax * coef[i, 0]) - intercept[i]) / coef[i, 1]
    ax.plot([xmin, xmax], [ymin, ymax],
             ls="--", color=color)
plt.legend()

Evaluation¶

  • In reality, we would probably not use all our training data set to fit the classifier.

  • We would use a part of it for training, and a part of it to evaluate our classifier.

  • A straightforward performance metric is accuracy: the proportion of instances correctly classified by the classifier.
In [30]:

Out[30]:
0.8125

  • So the classifier classifies correctly about 85% of our training data.

  • But actually this kind of performance measurement is flawed.

  • We must not measure the performance of the classifier on the training data.

  • We must check how the classifier does on some other data.

  • That's the data we held out from the training in the beginning.

In [31]:
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
Out[31]:
0.68421052631578949

  • So the performance with the test data is around 65%.

  • Note that since we partition the training set and the test set in random, the results we get may vary from run to run.

  • The most popular evaluation functions in scikit-learn are: accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score. In what follows, TP stands for True Positive, TN for True Negative, FP for False Positive, and FN for False Negative.

  • The accuracy, which we've already seen, is formally: $$ \frac{\textrm{TP} + \textrm{TN}}{\textrm{Sample Size}} $$

  • The precision is the ratio $$\frac{\textrm{TP}}{\textrm{TP} + \textrm{FP}}$$ The precision is intuitively the ability of the classifier not to label as positive a sample that is negative. The best value is 1 and the worst value is 0.
  • The recall is the ratio $$\frac{\textrm{TP}}{\textrm{TP} + \textrm{FN}}$$ The recall is intuitively the ability of the classifier to find all the positive samples. The best value is 1 and the worst value is 0.

  • The $F_1$ score takes both the precision and the recall into account.

  • Mathematically, it is the harmonic mean of the precision and the recall.

  • The harmonic mean of $n$ numbers $x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n$ is defined as:

$$H={\frac {n}{{\frac {1}{x_{1}}}+{\frac {1}{x_{2}}}+\cdots +{\frac {1}{x_{n}}}}}$$
  • So, the $F_1$ score is:
$$F_{1}=2\cdot \frac{1}{\tfrac{1}{\mathrm{recall}}+\tfrac{1}{\mathrm{precision}}} = 2\cdot {\frac{\mathrm{precision} \cdot \mathrm{recall}}{\mathrm{precision} +\mathrm{recall}}}$$
In [32]:
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=iris.target_names))

avg / total       0.65      0.68      0.65        38
  • The support is the number of samples of the y_test dataset that lie in that class.

  • Another useful metric is the confusion matrix.

  • Each cell $(i, j)$ in the confusion matrix contains the number of instances of class $i$ that were predicted to be in class $j$.

  • A good classifier will accumulate values on the diagonal.

  • There is a way to improve the validation of our model, called k-fold cross-validation.

  • In k-fold cross-validation, the original sample is randomly partitioned into $k$ equal sized subsamples.

  • Of the $k$ subsamples, a single subsample is retained as the validation data for testing the model, and the remaining $k − 1$ subsamples are used as training data.

  • The cross-validation process is then repeated $k$ times (the "folds"), with each of the $k$ subsamples used exactly once as the validation data.

  • The $k$ results from the folds can then be averaged (or otherwise combined) to produce a single estimation.

  • A variation of k-fold validation is stratified k-fold validation.

  • It returns stratified folds, where each set contains approximately the same percentage of samples of each target class as the complete set.

  • To simplify the whole process we'll use the Pipeline class.

  • The construction of the Pipeline class takes a list of (name, transform) tuples (implementing fit/transform) that are chained, in the order in which they are chained, with the last object an estimator.

  • In this way we'll combine the standard scaling and the classification.

In [34]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

clf = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ('linear_model', SGDClassifier())
    ])

  • Now we can get our validation scores.

  • We will use the cross_val_score method.

  • The cross_val_score takes a scoring parameter that indicates the score to calculate. It can be one of:

    • accuracy
    • recall
    • f1
    • etc.

  • It also takes a cv parameter. When it is an integer, it uses a k-fold strategy, or a stratifield k-fold strategy when the classifier is derived from ClassifierMixin (SGDClassifier is derived from ClassifierMixin).

Principal Component Analysis¶

  • Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is an important technique in Machine Learning, with many applications.

  • The idea is to convert a set of observations of possibly correlated variables into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components.

  • The number of principal components is less than the original number of variables.

  • The idea is that with the principal components we can capture essential aspects of the variables that correspond to the principal components.

  • Moreover, the principal components capture, in decreasing order, the variance exhibited by the original variables.

  • So the first principal component is the most important in that it captures more variance than any other component, the second principal component is the second in importance because it captures more variance than any other component bar the first component, etc.

  • PCA is a form of unsupervised learning, because we do not supply target values.

  • PCA is therefore particularly useful for dimensional reduction.

  • In dimensional reduction we want to reduce the number of dimensions that we handle (because the number is very big), yet without losing important information from our observations.

  • To do that, we perform PCA and we select as many principal components as we need to retain the characteristics of the original dimensions.

  • To see how this works, let's perform PCA on an image.

  • We are going to use an iconic image, Dorothea Lange's photo of the migrant mother.

  • This image is not already contained in scikit-learn, so we'll have to import it.

  • We need to install the Python Imaging Library for that.

  • We can do that with pip3 install pillow.

  • Then we read and display the image.

In [37]:

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
    plt.xticks(())
    plt.yticks(())
    plt.imshow(img,  cmap=plt.cm.gray)
    plt.title("height: %s width: %s size: %s" % (h, w, size))

  • We'll therefore create an array whose rows will be horizontal lines of the picture and columns will be vertical lines.

  • PCA is implemented through the PCA class and its subclasses.

  • We instantiate an estimator and then we fit with our data.

  • We treat our image as our dataset, having 692 features (our columns).

  • We'll perform PCA with 50 components.

  • In effect, we'll try to reduce the image so it is represented as an orthogonal transformation of the data using 50 components instead of the 692 original ones.

  • We have found the 50 principal components of our image.

  • Each component is a row (692 pixels).

  • Now we can project the original image on these components.
In [43]:
image_pca = pca.transform(image_array)
print(image_pca.shape)

(900, 50)
  • The image_pca array is the result of the following transformation:
$$ X P = Y $$

  • In the above formula, $P$ is a matrix containing the components we have found as columns, $X$ is a matrix containing our original data, and $Y$ is image_pca.

  • Since $X$ is a matrix with dimensions n_samples, n_features and $P$ is a matrix with dimensions n_features, n_components, $Y$ is a matrix with dimensions n_samples, n_components.

  • If we were to display the projection we would see a reduced image that, however, explains the variance of the 50 principal components of the original image.

In [44]:
show_image(image_pca, image_pca.shape[0], image_pca.shape[1], image_pca.size)

  • Although the above does not look like much, we can verify that it contains much of the information of the original image.

  • We can project the PCA image back to the original space by inverse_transform method.

  • So, the PCA image is a compressed version of the original image

  • Note that when we project back to the original space we return to the original image size, but below we display the PCA image size because that is what we have actually kept.

In [45]:
image_pca = pca.transform(image_array)
reduced_image = pca.inverse_transform(image_pca)
show_image(reduced_image, reduced_image.shape[0], reduced_image.shape[1], image_pca.size)
  • We can also see how much information is lost with different choices of the numbers of principal components.

def plot_gallery(images, titles, h, w, n_row=3, n_col=4):
    """Helper function to plot a gallery of portraits"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(1.8 * n_col, 2.4 * n_row))
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0, left=.01, right=.99, top=.90, hspace=.35)
    for i in range(n_row * n_col):
        plt.subplot(n_row, n_col, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i].reshape((h, w)), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
        plt.title(titles[i], size=12)
        plt.xticks(())
        plt.yticks(())

  • One of the tricky things with Machine Learning, and SVM, is knowing which parameter values to use for an estimator.

  • We can put scikit-learn to do the work for us by using the GridSearchCV class.

  • The GridSearchCV instance evaluates all the possible combinations of parameter values and retains the best combination.

  • By default, the parameter search uses the score function of the estimator to evaluate a parameter setting, but we can change that if we want.

def title(y_pred, y_test, target_names, i):
    pred_name = target_names[y_pred[i]].rsplit(' ', 1)[-1]
    true_name = target_names[y_test[i]].rsplit(' ', 1)[-1]
    return 'predicted: %s\ntrue:      %s' % (pred_name, true_name)

prediction_titles = [title(y_pred, y_test, target_names, i)
